  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in virtually every country in the world.\n\n*   **Globally:** International organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set standards and recommendations for combating money laundering and terrorist financing, which most countries adhere to.\n\n*   **Specific Countries:**\n\n    *   **United States:** The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), as amended by the USA PATRIOT Act, is the primary legislation against money laundering.\n    *   **United Kingdom:** The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 is the key legislation.\n    *   **European Union:** The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives, which member states must implement into their national laws.\n    *   **Canada:** The Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA) is the main law.\n\nThese laws generally make it illegal to:\n\n*   Conceal or disguise the nature, source, location, disposition, movement, or ownership of illegally obtained funds.\n*   Use illegally obtained funds to promote further criminal activity.\n*   Transfer funds to avoid reporting requirements.\n*   Assist someone else in money laundering.\n\nMoney laundering laws also require financial institutions and other businesses to:\n\n*   Implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n*   Identify and verify their customers (Know Your Customer - KYC).\n*   Report suspicious activity.\n*   Keep records of transactions.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and forfeiture of assets.\n\nIn short, money laundering is illegal and heavily regulated worldwide.\n",
